This type of gold-copper-plated helmet with a brow plate has also been found in other notable sites such as the {{ill|Nintoku Kofun|ja|仁徳陵}}, Kitatenhirazuka Kofun in Osaka, {{ill|Gojō Nekozuka Kofun|ja|五条猫塚古墳}} in Nara, Sakume Kofun in Mie, {{ill|Tsukioka Kofun|ja|月岡古墳}} in Fukuoka, and Gionyama Kofun in Chiba. Based on the artifacts, the mound is estimated to have been constructed in the late 5th century.{{Sfn|Suenaga|1934}}
== Mound Investigation == In 1981, the Osaka Prefectural Board of Education conducted an excavation of the mound. The vertical stone chamber had already been flattened and lost, but remnants of paving stones and a haniwa (clay figurine) arrangement were well-preserved. The original diameter of the mound is estimated to have been 50 meters, with a height of 7 meters, and it was constructed in two tiers. A protruding area (造り出し) was identified on the northwest side. Traces of a surrounding moat were inferred from the paddy field ridges in the vicinity. The excavated haniwa included cylindrical, bell-shaped, and lid-shaped types, with 15% of them made from high-hardness Sue ware. The paving stones were made from Izumi sandstone, sourced locally.{{Sfn|Kuze|1968}}
== Cultural Properties == === Important Cultural Property (National Designation) === - Gold-copper-plated helmet with brow plate from Nishikoyama Kofun, Izumi Province (archaeological material). Designated on August 26, 1938.{{Sfn|Cultural Property Database|201}}{{Sfn|Osaka Prefectural Website}} - Note: This artifact was stolen in 1955.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Press Release, 2017}}
