'''Nishikoyama Kofun''' (にしこやまこふん) is a mid-{{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代}} Kofun located in Tannowa, Misaki Town, Sennan District, Osaka Prefecture. It is part of the {{ill|Tannowa Kofun Cluster|ja|淡輪古墳群}}, which also includes the {{ill|Nishiryo Kofun|ja|西陵古墳}}.
== Overview == The Nishikoyama Kofun is a scallop-shaped Kofun with a diameter of 50 meters, located near {{ill|Nishiryo Kofun|ja|西陵古墳}} and {{ill|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun|ja|淡輪ニサンザイ古墳}}. The mound was excavated in 1930 under the direction of {{ill|Masao Suenaga|ja|末永雅雄}} from the Kyoto University Archaeology Laboratory. A vertical stone chamber measuring 3.3 meters in length and 0.7 meters in width was discovered at the mound's summit. burial goods recovered from the stone chamber included: - 23 {{ill|Iron swords|ja|直刀}} - 2 spears - 107 iron arrowheads - Triangular plate-riveted {{ill|Tankō|ja|短甲|1=Tankō}} - A gold-copper-plated riveted {{ill|Helmet with Brow Plate|ja|眉庇付冑|1=Helmet with Brow Plate}} - A riveted neck guard and shoulder guards - Approximately 800 lamellar plates for {{ill|Lamellar armour|lt=Keikō (lamellar armour)|ja|挂甲}}
This type of gold-copper-plated helmet with a brow plate has also been found in other notable sites such as the {{ill|Nintoku Kofun|ja|仁徳陵}}, Kitatenhirazuka Kofun in Osaka, {{ill|Gojō Nekozuka Kofun|ja|五条猫塚古墳}} in Nara, Sakume Kofun in Mie, {{ill|Tsukioka Kofun|ja|月岡古墳}} in Fukuoka, and Gionyama Kofun in Chiba. Based on the burial goods, the mound is estimated to have been constructed in the late 5th century.{{Sfn|Suenaga|1934}}
== Mound Investigation == In 1981, the Osaka Prefectural Board of Education conducted an excavation of the mound. The vertical stone chamber had already been flattened and lost, but remnants of paving stones and a haniwa (clay figurine) arrangement were well-preserved. The original diameter of the mound is estimated to have been 50 meters, with a height of 7 meters, and it was constructed in two tiers. A protruding area (造り出し) was identified on the northwest side. Traces of a surrounding moat were inferred from the paddy field ridges in the vicinity. The excavated haniwa included cylindrical, bell-shaped, and lid-shaped types, with 15% of them made from high-hardness Sue pottery. The paving stones were made from Izumi sandstone, sourced locally.{{Sfn|Kuze|1968}}
== Historic Site == === Important designation1 (National designation1) === - Gold-copper-plated helmet with brow plate from Nishikoyama Kofun, Izumi Province (archaeological material). Designated on August 26, 1938.{{Sfn|designation1 Database|201}}{{Sfn|Osaka Prefectural Website}} ** Note: This artifact was stolen in 1955.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Press Release, 2017}}
