'''Nishikoyama Kofun''' (にしこやまこふん) is a mid-{{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofun period|qq=}} Kofun located in Tannowa, Misaki Town, Sennan District, Osaka Prefecture. It is part of the {{ill|Tannowa Kofun Cluster|ja|淡輪古墳群|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tannowa Kofun Cluster|qq=}}, which also includes the {{ill|Nishiryo Kofun|ja|西陵古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishiryo Kofun|qq=}}.

== Overview ==
The Nishikoyama Kofun is a scallop-shaped Kofun with a diameter of 50 meters, located near {{ill|Nishiryo Kofun|ja|西陵古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishiryo Kofun|qq=}} and {{ill|Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun|ja|淡輪ニサンザイ古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tannowa Nisanzai Kofun|qq=}}. The mound was excavated in 1930 under the direction of {{ill|Masao Suenaga|ja|末永雅雄|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Masao Suenaga|qq=}} from the Kyoto University Archaeology Laboratory. A vertical stone chamber measuring 3.3 meters in length and 0.7 meters in width was discovered at the mound's summit. burial goods recovered from the stone chamber included:
- 23 {{ill|Iron swords|ja|直刀|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iron swords|qq=}}
- 2 spears
- 107 iron arrowheads
- Triangular plate-riveted {{ill|Tankō|ja|短甲|1=Tankō|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tankō|13=User:Immanuelle/Tankō|qq=}}
- A gold-copper-plated riveted {{ill|Helmet with Brow Plate|ja|眉庇付冑|1=Helmet with Brow Plate|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Helmet with Brow Plate|13=User:Immanuelle/Helmet with Brow Plate|qq=}}
- A riveted neck guard and shoulder guards
- Approximately 800 lamellar plates for {{ill|Lamellar armour|lt=Keikō (lamellar armour)|ja|挂甲|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lamellar armour|qq=}}

This type of gold-copper-plated helmet with a brow plate has also been found in other notable sites such as the {{ill|Daisenryō Kofun|ja|仁徳陵|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nintoku Kofun|qq=}}, Kitatenhirazuka Kofun in Osaka, {{ill|Gojō Nekozuka Kofun|ja|五条猫塚古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gojō Nekozuka Kofun|qq=}} in Nara, Sakume Kofun in Mie, {{ill|Tsukioka Kofun|ja|月岡古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukioka Kofun|qq=}} in Fukuoka, and Gionyama Kofun in Chiba. Based on the burial goods, the mound is estimated to have been constructed in the late 5th century.{{Sfn|Suenaga|1934}}

== Mound Investigation ==
In 1981, the Osaka Prefectural Board of Education conducted an excavation of the mound. The vertical stone chamber had already been flattened and lost, but remnants of paving stones and a haniwa (clay figurine) arrangement were well-preserved. The original diameter of the mound is estimated to have been 50 meters, with a height of 7 meters, and it was constructed in two tiers. A protruding area (造り出し) was identified on the northwest side. Traces of a surrounding moat were inferred from the paddy field ridges in the vicinity. The excavated haniwa included cylindrical, bell-shaped, and lid-shaped types, with 15% of them made from high-hardness Sue pottery. The paving stones were made from Izumi sandstone, sourced locally.{{Sfn|Kuze|1968}}

== Historic Site ==
=== Important designation1 (National designation1) ===
- Gold-copper-plated helmet with brow plate from Nishikoyama Kofun, Izumi Province (archaeological material). Designated on August 26, 1938.{{Sfn|designation1 Database|201}}{{Sfn|Osaka Prefectural Website}}
** Note: This artifact was stolen in 1955.{{Sfn|Agency for Cultural Affairs, Press Release, 2017}}

== References ==
* {{Cite book|title=Centennial Memorial of Masao Suenaga: The Progress of Kofun Research|publisher=Osaka Sayama Municipal Local Museum|year=1997|pages=22}}
* {{Cite book|title=Tannowa Site Excavation Summary III|year=1981|pages=56-67}}
* {{Cite book|author=Hitoshi Kuze|title=The Story of Izumi Archaeological Sites|year=2004|pages=7-10}}

